entry.title: Add UMA histogram for causes of irregular LCP image load timing
entry.content:
This CL adds a UMA histogram to count the causes of irregular LCP image

load timing. This is a follow up CL to the previous

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4476487 in

that specific potential causes are being counted. They are

1, image being loaded from memory cache.

2, image being preloaded by the early-hints mechanism.

3, image being loaded from memory cache and preloaded by the early-hints

mechanism.

If none of the above is true when the load timing is incorrect, we

count the cause as unknown.



The information whether an image being loaded from memory cache and/or

preloaded by the early-hints mechanism are propagated from the

ResourceFetcher::RequestResource and passed from renderer to browser.



The UMA recording happens in the PageLoadTracker::OnTimingChanged()

method when a new LCP candidate is about to be updated.

entry.title: Implement flushing of properties immediately
entry.content:
* Previously, properties from http_server_properties were flushed once every 60 seconds

which was extremely hard to test from Cronet as the tests had to poll and wait for 60 seconds.

This introduced flakiness and long-running tests which we wanted to avoid.

* This CL introduces a new method that flushes the properties to the disk immediately. The flushing

is a sync operation as this will only be used for testing and there is no need to make it async.

* Decreased the runtime of each test from an average of 70s to 1s

entry.title: Add remoting-crash-uploader binary and friends
entry.content:
This CL adds a few classes and a binary which will be used to upload

CRD crash reports generated on linux. I've put the impls into a

crash-specific sub-directory as I'd like to reuse the impl for Mac as

well.



A brief overview of the crash lifecycle as it is implemented:



1) CRD binary crashes, an in-proc breakpad instance writes a dmp file:

/tmp/chromoting/.dmp

2) Breakpad calls our post-dmp handler which writes a metadata file:

/tmp/chromoting/.json



3) CrashFileWatcher instance sees the new metadata file and verifies

the dump file also exists

4) CrashFileWatcher instance moves the dmp and json file into:

/tmp/chromoting/

5) CrashFileWatcher signals CrashFileUploader that there is a dmp file

ready to be processed

6) CrashFileUploader reads the dmp and metadata contents and does some

validation on tham

7) CrashFileUploader generates a POST request and sends it to the Crash

collector service

8) CrashFileUploader deletes the dmp file and writes an upload_result

file with the result of the action



For #8, I want to leave the dir and metadata file around

for troubleshooting. For instance if someone says they experienced a

crash on their host, we can ask for the specific report_id which is

stored in the upload_result file.



Once this lands, I will follow up with a CL which incorporates the new

crash-uploader binary into the daemon script.

entry.title: ADPF - boost frame in the middle if frame production takes too long
entry.content:
The idea is:

- Start a timer in OnBeginFrame (with the deadline = ADPF target duration * const multiplier)

- If the frame production is finished before the timer expires (i.e. if AttempDrawAndSwap is called), cancel the timer

- Otherwise, report a fake actual_duration > target_duration to ask ADPF for extra CPU resources, so that the frame has a higher chance of getting produced before the system deadline



Local manual scrolling tests show some scroll jank reduction, but:

- The data is noisy, so it's hard to quantify the improvement (or even to be sure that it's actually an improvement)

- This can cause power usage increase



I believe we need a field experiment to see the impact.

entry.title: [Passwords] Fix mismatch in enums.xml for ProvisionalSaveFailure
entry.content:
It looks like enums.xml diverged from what the code actually records in

M86, with https://crrev.com/c/2265404.



One factor that may have played a role is that the enum definition

didn't follow the recommended practices to add a comment and specify

explicit values per bucket, both of which are now addressed in this

patch.



This also means the pre-existing metric merges incompatible data and

hence is impossible to analyze accurately without a version filter. M85

is already old (presumably negligible data volume) but the proposal in

this patch is to introduce a new metric that isn't affected by this

bug (i.e. rename the metric).

entry.title: p2p: Introduce SendBatch.
entry.content:
This CL introduces a default-off feature WebRtcSendPacketBatch under

which P2PSocketClientImpl collects batchable packets until a packet

completing the batch appears at the socket client. On receiving the

batch, the network service does the related work and then emits a new

SendBatchComplete mojo call. The result is drastically reduced IPC,

measured at up to 87% less under the feature for a Meet 1080p call.



Stray non-batchable packets incoming during the collection of a batch

is added to the batch and sent when the batch completion call comes.



A sampling of WebRTC.P2P.UDP.BatchingNumberOfSentPackets under Meet

720p looks like follows:



0 O (0 = 0.0%)

1 --------------------------------O (3470 = 64.5%) {0.0%}

2 -O (63 = 1.2%) {64.5%}

3 --------O (393 = 7.3%) {65.7%}

4 ---------------O (739 = 13.7%) {73.0%}

5 -----O (252 = 4.7%) {86.8%}

7 ----------O (459 = 8.5%) {91.5%}

9 ...



71% of the packets were batched.

entry.title: media/gpu/chromeos: Handle error if wrapping VideoFrame failed
entry.content:
VideoFrame::WrapVideoFrame() call may fail if the frame has invalid

attributes (size, format, etc.). In that situation, the wrap will fail

and will return an nullptr.



In some cases, the decoding component may send the invalid frame sizes

on purpose, for example in the Android STS. Without the DCHECK enabled,

the Chrome GPU process will crash on the locking attemption. If the GPU

process won't be restarted fast enough, the STS will fail because the

backend won't be able to get any GPU backend.



In any case, crash in such cases is not the best way of handling the

error, so the DCHECK checking for the wrapped frame was replaced with

the if, and the nullptr is returned.

entry.title: media: Use RAII-like pattern for VADisplayState.
entry.content:
The VADisplayState is a singleton class that keeps track of a VADisplay.

Chrome uses a single VADisplay to make libva calls, and it currently

does manual reference counting to track the initialization state: the

VADisplayState is initialized for the first reference and re-used

thereafter; then it's de-initialized after the last reference is

released. To do this reference counting, users of VADisplayState must

call VADisplayState::Initialize() before using the VADisplayState

singleton and then call VADisplayState::Deinitialize() when they're

done.



Unfortunately, as explained in https://crbug.com/1435500#c41, it's very

easy to forget to call Deinitialize(), and this can actually cause the

GPU process to crash.



This CL refactors the VADisplayState a bit to make it use a RAII-like

pattern. After this CL, users of VADisplayState (now renamed to VADisplayStateSingleton in this CL) no longer need to call

Initialize()/Deinitialize(). Instead, they acquire a

VADisplayStateHandle: if this handle is non-null, users can assume the

VADisplayStateSingleton is initialized. When the VADisplayStateHandle is

destroyed (e.g., by going out of scope), the VADisplayStateSingleton's

reference count is decremented automatically and de-initialization is

performed as needed.



Note: I did consider using a scoped_refptr, but the details make using

this a bit more complicated than it may seem at a first glance: what

we're ref-counting is not the lifetime of an object, but rather its

initialization state. If we use a scoped_refptr, we may hand out a

reference to a VADisplayStateSingleton that will soon be de-initialized.



Note: after this CL, we no longer log vaTerminate() failures for UMA.



Bug: 1435500

Test: on grunt - make sure the GPU process can start after initializing the VADisplayState fails.

entry.title: Implementation for systemEntropy in PerformanceNavigationTiming
entry.content:
To enable developers to discern if the page load occurs during a

non-optimal performance state, we will add a new ‘systemEntropy’ field

to the PerformanceNavigationTiming struct. This would be a new enum

representing the state of the user agent at the time the navigation was

started.



enum NavigationEntropy {

"high",

"normal"

};



Chromium will return a ‘high’ entropy for all top level navigations

that occur between the start of the browser process up until the first

visible page completes loading.



Because navigations can be script-initiated (iframes, prerenders) the

entropy state will be empty for all non-top-level navigation. This

voids this value being used as a proxy for querying the system entropy

in real time.





Explainer: https://github.com/MicrosoftEdge/MSEdgeExplainers/blob/main/PerformanceNavigationTiming%20for%20User%20Agent%20Launch/explainer.md

Chrome Status: https://chromestatus.com/feature/5186950448283648

Dev Design: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1D6DqptsCEd3wPRsZ0q1iwVBAXXmhxZuLV-KKFI0ptCg/edit?usp=sharing

I2P: https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/blink-dev/c/o0F7nBKsgg0/m/bJSp3ekfAAAJ



Manual testing steps:



1) Start the browser with these command line parameters:

--enable-features=PerformanceNavigateSystemEntropy https://example.com

2) Open the developer tools, and switch to the Console tool.

3) Run "window.performance.getEntriesByType('navigation')[0].systemEntropy"

(without the double quotes) into the console, and you should see 'high' returned.



Bug: 1413848
